+// ── Exp3-IX (Exponential weights for Exploration + Exploitation) ─────────────
+//
+// Why Exp3 instead of UCB1:
+//   Pokémon is a *simultaneous-move* game — both players pick actions at the
+//   same time.  UCB1 assumes a single maximizing agent; applying it to both
+//   sides independently creates a deterministic joint policy that an adversary
+//   can exploit (provably sub-optimal regardless of iteration count).
+//
+//   Exp3 maintains a *mixed strategy* (probability distribution over moves)
+//   per side and updates multiplicatively: w_i *= exp(η * r̂_i).
+//   This is the adversarial bandit algorithm; it converges to Nash equilibrium.
+//
+// Implementation notes:
+//   - Weights are stored in linear scale (initialized to 1.0), NOT log scale.
+//     This means the update is w_i *= exp(η * r̂_i), but to avoid allocations
+//     during the hot-path sampling we just sum weights and sample proportionally.
+//   - Implicit exploration: γ-fraction of probability mass is spread uniformly,
+//     ensuring every action has probability ≥ γ/K.  This bounds the importance
+//     weight and prevents variance blowup.
+//   - Zero heap allocations in the hot path: sampling uses a single cumulative
+//     pass over the (stack-small) move list; no Vec, no WeightedIndex.
+//
+// Hyperparameters:
+//   EXP3_ETA  = learning rate.  Optimal for K actions and T iterations:
+//               η* = sqrt(ln K / (K·T)).  For K≈9, T≈80k: η* ≈ 0.0018.
+//               We use 0.003 (slightly aggressive to adapt within a turn).
+//   EXP3_GAMMA = implicit exploration fraction.  γ=0.05 means each action
+//                gets at least 0.05/9 ≈ 0.006 probability regardless of weights.
+const EXP3_ETA: f32 = 0.003;
+const EXP3_GAMMA: f32 = 0.05;
